### 2.  Two people board at floor 1, one gets off at floor 10, the other at floor 30  

The lift must travel from floor 1 to floor 30 (the higher destination) and stop at floor 10 on the way.  
Thus the lift’s travel consists of two *separate* trips:

* **Trip A:** floor 1 → floor 10  
* **Trip B:** floor 10 → floor 30  

We compute the time for each trip using the same method as in Q1, but with the appropriate distances.

| Trip | Distance (m) | \(s_{\text{acc}}\) (m) | \(t_{\text{acc}}\) (s) | \(s_{\text{const}}\) (m) | \(t_{\text{const}}\) (s) | \(t_{\text{dec}}\) (s) | Total (s) |
|------|--------------|----------------------|----------------------|------------------------|------------------------|----------------------|-----------|
| 1→10 | \(10 \times 5 = 50\) | \(12.5\) | \(5\) | \(50-2\cdot12.5 = 25\) | \(25/5 = 5\) | \(5\) | \(5+5+5 = 15\) |
| 10→30| \(20 \times 5 = 100\) | \(12.5\) | \(5\) | \(100-2\cdot12.5 = 75\) | \(75/5 = 15\) | \(5\) | \(5+15+5 = 25\) |

**Total time** = time for Trip A + time for Trip B = \(15\ \text{s} + 25\ \text{s} = \boxed{40\ \text{s}}\).

*(Note: The lift does not need to stop at floor 1 again; the second passenger boards at floor 10 and the lift continues upward.)*

